[2026-01-21 10:03:47] [INFO] Full LLM response:
Consider the `SimpleGraph.binomialRandom` definition and the property of `compl` on simple graphs. The complement of a graph $G$ corresponds to taking the complement of its edge set within the set of all possible edges (i.e., `diagSetᶜ`). The `binomialRandom` measure is defined as the pullback of the Bernoulli measure on `diagSetᶜ` along `edgeSet`. The Bernoulli measure with parameter $p$ maps to the Bernoulli measure with parameter $\sigma p = 1 - p$ under the set complement map (relative to the support). Therefore, we can use the commutation of `map` and `comap` to prove the result.

```lean
lemma IsBinomialRandom.compl (hG : IsBinomialRandom G p P) :
    IsBinomialRandom (fun ω ↦ (G ω)ᶜ) (σ p) P where
  map_eq := by
    rw [hG.map_eq, binomialRandom, binomialRandom,
      Measure.map_comap_map edgeSet_injective measurable_compl measurable_edgeSet
      (measurable_const.diff measurable_id) (fun G ↦ by simp [edgeSet_compl])]
    congr 1
    exact bernoulliOn_map_compl
```
